First, transform the sample counts of a taxa abundance matrix for the function of `otu`s realtive abundance instead. 
Ordinate: multivariate method of gradient analysis. `NMDS` operates on a distance matrix. Distance=bray is a character string and is the default setting. It is used if distance is the chosen matrix. Then plot the ordination plot, coloring by loaction. 

**Q**: There was no color present in the map, so you cant tell the samples apart. 

Relative abundance --> this is why we divide each otu by the sum of all otus  
```{r}
ps.prop <- transform_sample_counts(ps, function(otu) otu/sum(otu))
ord.nmds.bray <- ordinate(ps.prop, method="NMDS", distance="bray")
plot_ordination(physeq = ps.prop, ordination = ord.nmds.bray, color="Location", title="Bray NMDS")
``` 

`top20` pulls out the top 20 ASVs and saves it in an object. 
